node.text:
Tackling an LR + PS edit with a recent image from a blue hour ski in the mountains. So satisfying to have in body stabilization nowadays, using slow shutter speeds + low iso make for cleaner images long after the sun has set. 

Let me know what else you’d like to see edited!

Music: Two One, Four - @fyfemusic

node.text:
Chasing success, striving to be the “best” will make you unhappy because those are things that others measure for you. It’s external. 

Fulfillment however is something you can measure, only you. It’s internal. 

And as photographers we tend to put a lot of imaginary barriers that prevent us from being fulfilled in our craft. 

Heading into the new year, I’ve made a new workshop to help you remove those barriers. (Hint: they’re mostly within our heads). 

Goal setting, motivation, systems and routines... I cover it all. 

The workshop is on a limited pre-order. Link in bio :)

node.text:
Thrilled to bring you my new baby: Adventure Photography Pro Workshop.

Here’s what you need to know:
+ It’s made for rising photographers who want to get much better at selling their ideas to brands and getting hired. + it’s on a pre-order for a few days (save $$)
+ It comes with 12 months of free updates.
+ it gives you access to our @strohlworks grant so you can get $5k to make a dream project happen.
+ get 12 months of access to our Community board so you can get feedback on your work and pitch decks.

The Adventure Photo workshop is closing to admissions tomorrow night. After 2 years and thousands of students in it’s time to make room for new workshops... If you want lifetime access to the definitive guide to adventure photo I hope you’ll consider joining before it closes. 
It’s on its lowest price since pre-order — workshop.alexstrohl.com

node.title: The Adventure Photo Workshop is closing to admissions 🚀— bit.ly/awclosing

node.text:
@peakdesign Tripod on Kickstarter: https://bit.ly/PDtripod - I have had a long and bumpy history with tripods. 
One of them fell into a lake with my 5DS & a nice lens when I was shooting stars. So ever since then I've been a bit bitter about them. Until now. I've been working with @peakdesign field reviewing their first tripod and I think my dark tripod days are over...

node.title: Peak Design Tripod: First FIELD Review

node.text:
Sunset at 6500ft in the North Cascades. Seems like no matter where you go here, you always see Mt Baker towering over the landscape.. 

On the second image you can see @isaacsjohnston up the final ladder returning from his morning wee. 

And on the third image: still Mt Baker on the right, as if to prove my point!

node.text: @CanonUSA challenged me to pick my 5 all time favorite photos so I rolled up my sleeves and dug through the 250k+ image archive and selected these. Here’s why.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Alex Strohl on July 17, 2021. May be an image of sky.

node.text: Being precariously perched 2000ft over a glacier in a 90 year old structure isn’t exactly a recipe for a peaceful night of sleep but those first rays of sun promptly make you forget all about it… what a challenging fun jaunt getting up here @isaacsjohnston @66north

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Alex Strohl on July 11, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: Things look different when you’re alone. Even when going out with a group I like taking in some moments on my own to quiet the mind and really observe what’s going on. This is one of those scenes that sums up Glacier N.P- icebergs & beargrass - and I might have missed it if I didn’t slow down.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Alex Strohl on July 08, 2021 tagging @66north, and @isaacsjohnston. May be an image of mountain and nature.

node.text:
One of those 10pm summer sunsets where the colors in the sky linger for hours on end, seemingly unbothered by the inevitable darkness. 

Oh and I can’t believe its taken me 4 years to climb this mountain — made the first time extra special… @isaacsjohnston @66north
